Czech Railways has invested more than CZK 31 billion in vehicle modernization.
They have air conditioning and new toilets.
In the last six years, the state-owned carrier has invested more than CZK 31 billion in vehicle modernization.
A third of the carriages are currently equipped with air conditioning, about half of the trains have a new system of closed toilets.
However, the amounts for modernization in individual years, with the exception of 2012, are gradually decreasing.
In the last six years, Czech Railways has invested more than CZK 31 billion in vehicle modernization.
A third of the carriages are currently equipped with air conditioning, about half of the trains have a new system of closed toilets.
The money spent resulted in a reduction in the average age by two years for locomotives and stand-alone units and by six years for conventional wagons.
The carrier invested a larger share of its investment in regional transport, where about 60 percent of the money was directed, and the company invested 40 percent in the renewal of long-distance vehicles.
The average age of locomotives and units is currently 19 years.
However, upgraded older vehicles are counted as brand new in this indicator.
If vehicle modernizations were not taken into account, the average age of ČD traction vehicles would increase by ten years.
On average, passenger wagons are slightly older, with an average age of 23 years when modernisations are taken into account.
If only the age from the date of manufacture is taken into account, the average age of these vehicles would be 33.4 years.
However, classic trains consisting of wagons and hauled by a locomotive have gradually disappeared from the Czech and worldwide railways in recent years and are being replaced by motor or electric units.
Between 2011 and 2015, the number of locomotives decreased from 280 to 223 pieces, and the number of classic wagons dropped from 2716 in 2011 to 2132 in the middle of this year.
In particular, the carrier got rid of old vehicles equipped with leatherette seats and doors without the possibility of blocking the opening while driving.
Between January and July, the carrier had 110 of these cars scrapped.
Among the investments that ČD plans to make in the vehicle fleet in the near future, it is possible to mention, for example, the purchase of 50 wagons for speeds of up to 200 kilometres per hour, which the carrier plans to deploy on the international route Prague - Bratislava - Budapest, or a framework contract for the purchase of electric units for domestic express lines.
The contract provides for the purchase of up to 30 pieces of motor and 20 pieces of electric units.
The authorities have known about illegal advertising for a quarter of a year, they are unable to get rid of it.
We are completely helpless, they admit.
For a quarter of a year, the editors of the online daily Aktuálně.cz have been following the story of a billboard in South Bohemia, which now attracts motorists to visit Lipno, where there is not only an interesting walk in the treetops, but also the Olympic Park.
Highway administrators know they are standing there illegally, but they say they can't do anything about it.
There are hundreds, maybe thousands, of similar ads across the country.
According to officials, the fault lies with a flimsy law that makes it impossible to remove illegal mobile billboards immediately.
What is needed is a complicated bureaucratic wheel.
In the meantime, however, the company changes its name and the office is short for it.
Or just move the ad a few meters and the official process has to start again.
A quarter of a year ago, the Road and Motorway Directorate admitted: on the main road from České Budějovice to Lipno, there is an advertising billboard on our land by the state road on the black.
But even three months were not enough for officials to get rid of an unauthorized portable structure with a giant advertising poster.
As if no one minded that he was standing right next to the road, in a fifty-meter protective zone, where nothing was allowed to stand for safety.
Road managers say they simply can't deal with the billboard because of the leaky law.
Maybe load it up and drive it away.
"We can't afford that," says Nina Ledvinová, spokeswoman for the Road and Motorway Directorate, referring to the complicated bureaucratic wheel that the removal of the billboard must be preceded by law.
The case of this particular billboard, whose fate the online daily Aktuálně.cz began to follow in detail in the spring, is not unique and points to a general problem that the state and the authorities cannot solve effectively and quickly.
In South Bohemia alone, the editorial office counted dozens of similar mobile ads placed against the rules right next to or near the road.
The situation is similar in other regions.
"We have trouble forcing companies to remove the banners," confirms Jiří Klása, head of the transport department of the České Budějovice regional authority, whose colleagues deal with similar stories.
According to Klása, the culprit is a leaky law that binds officials.
First, he has to intricately approach the owner of the billboard to give the ad away.
But company bosses are often unbeatable, or they know the trick that Aktuálně.cz have already described in the past, when they began to take a closer look at the issue: just move the mobile advertising stand a few meters and officials can throw the previous call to remove black advertising in the trash.
This is because the authority must determine exactly where the illegal billboard stands.
"If someone moves it and the coordinates suddenly disagree, it is seen as a new device and we have to address the owner again," explains Jiří Klása.
The new law will not help.
A change could be brought by a new law that will ban billboards on motorways from September next year and restrict them on category I roads.
Critics point out that the rules for combating illegal and easily portable advertising will remain the same as before.
And the authorities will not be relieved.
Companies can continue to earn tens to hundreds of millions of crowns a year from renting illegal space, and no one can pay for them.
For example, the billboard attracting to Lipno belongs to the company Commerz Billboard.
Officials know her well: the České Budějovice municipality is currently conducting three administrative proceedings against her for illegally erected billboards.
The company faces a fine of three hundred thousand crowns in each proceeding.
These are multiple advertisements that were placed without permission in the protective zone of a class I road.
The proceedings have not yet been completed, says Jaroslav Mráz, head of the Transport Department of the České Budějovice City Hall.
The ad that Aktuálně.cz is interested in is not yet one of these cases, but it will most likely be added soon.
According to RMD spokeswoman Nina Ledvinová, the company did not respond to repeated written calls for removal, and the case will thus reach the table of regional and then probably municipal officials.
Commerz Billboard is one of those suspicious companies that cannot be contacted.
She does not take over the post office and closed her official headquarters in Žižkov more than six years ago.
It's not even clear who is behind it.
In the past, the company's post office went to the South Bohemian businessman Anton Fischer, who became famous for a sharp dispute with the head of the Czech representation of the Hyundai brand.
Fischer, whose company Euro Billboard leases the space from Comerz Billboard and offers it to advertisers, has denied any connection in the past.
However, this spring, when RMD began to be interested in advertising Lipno at the instigation of Aktuálně.cz, Fischer had state officials send a letter to the mysterious company Commerz Billboard to his guesthouse, where the company is allegedly based.
Even from this address, however, no one has contacted the highway administrators to this day.
A futile struggle.
Such silence or opaque changes of settlements are not uncommon.
A few years ago, we gradually fined one company two million crowns.
But it changed the name and ID number and there was nothing to solve.
The bailiff returned the case, the ads continued to stand, perhaps in other places.
We are quite powerless against such companies and their business practices.
It's like fighting windmills, one official admits on condition of anonymity.
The amendment to the law in this respect has not yet been addressed.
Aktuálně.cz spoke to several Members who were interested in the issue.
But they have not yet developed any activity.
On the contrary, there were deputies who wanted to extend the deadline for preserving billboards on the main Czech roads.
The government refused.
Billboards are not only for national, but also regional and municipal politicians a very sensitive and somewhat schizophrenic topic.
On the one hand, they know about the social demand to limit them, on the other hand, they themselves need them for advertising in election campaigns.
I do not hold the relatively established impression that if something does not work, then it is necessary to change the laws.
Farmers will harvest less grain this year, but more rapeseed and poppy seeds, statisticians estimate.
