Russia and Turkey: An alliance of the "incompatible"?
It was a gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce the formal end of an eight-month-long war of words and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin greeted his Turkish counterpart in the sumptuous hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted this reconciliation more.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin wasn't smiling, and he barely radiated warmth, even by his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken about his "dear friend" Mr. Putin - five times, according to one of the reports.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre-crisis levels, but would be even better.
The next day, a local newspaper wrote that Erdogan had behaved as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm revealed the exact opposite.
But the lingering coldness that emanated from Putin showed that the Russian leader had forgotten nothing.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: Turkey's downing of a Russian warplane on the Syrian border.
Moscow's reaction at the time was furious.
Putin threw punches around and accused Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The scandal was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding true trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
For months, the state-controlled media has waged a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara.
Suddenly, it seemed as if the Turks were to blame for everything.
More serious were allegations from top officials that Erdogan's own family benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He emphatically denied this.
But in St. Petersburg came the official message that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting took place only because Putin received the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared a kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a ceasefire are clear.
First and foremost, Erdogan was nearly removed from power in a failed coup last month and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have visibly shaken him as well.
There is also an economic motive.
Russian sanctions have had a hard impact - in particular, the cancellation of charter flights that annually carry several million Russian tourists to the coast of Turkey.
This number has decreased by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies will certainly breathe a sigh of relief when flights are eventually resumed.
They make money from Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as a report in the newspaper Vedemosti proclaimed.
But the visit had another political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry at the West for what it sees as a poor response to the coup attempt.
In addition, long-standing hostility has led to lengthy talks on EU accession and the entry of Putin - who is eager to take advantage of the cooling and sever Turkey's ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly got bonus points when Ankara asked for help from elected authorities after the coup attempt.
You have to understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-seated fear of regime change, this is a given.
So the summit in this pompous, seaside palace allowed Russia and Turkey to demonstrate what one analyst described to me as an "alliance of the incompatible": how two countries that feel rejected and used by the West join forces.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly demonstrated mutual reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently positioned itself as a peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey are on opposite sides.
You could say that after nearly three hours of initial talks, the two presidents said at a press conference that they had not even mentioned the issue.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answering a question about the differences between them, while Putin chose to highlight these differences.
There is no clear agreement on the basis of which the two states can find common ground on Syria.
But after months of open hostility - and given the risk of utter disaster when NATO member Turkey shot down a Russian warplane - it is surely better that the two leaders are at least talking again.
