In England, about 140,000 people suffer a heart attack each year, and a quarter of them suffer another attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by the accumulation of fat, which forms a continuous layer on the walls of the arteries.
If this layer is torn off, a blood clot may form, blockage blood access to the heart and heart attack may develop.
If the clot is released, it can continue through the bloodstream, blocking the blood supply to the brain and causing a stroke.
People who have already had a heart attack are at higher risk of having another attack.
Ticagrelor, which is manufactured by Britain's AstraZeneca and sold under the brand name Brilique, reduces the risk by making clots less likely to form.
The NICE draft directive published today recommends that patients receive 90 mg of ticagrelor for 12 months and then 60 mg together with aspirin, twice a day for the next three years.
Professor Carole Longson, director of the NICE Centre for Technology Assessment, said: "Despite the availability of effective secondary preventive treatment, there is a quarter of patients who have had a heart attack and who suffer another heart attack or stroke – often with devastating consequences.
