Court in France refuses to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A court in France has rejected an order by authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, home to thousands of refugees.
During a court hearing this week, authorities in Calais argued that the state should be allowed to close a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods ranging from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, sell tea for 50 cents or basic meals for a few euros in makeshift restaurants.
The office of the prefect of Calais argued that the sites needed to be demolished because they were a parallel economy that did not pay taxes and because they posed fire hazards and health risks.
Aid agencies told the court that shops and restaurants were vital and that the free meals offered by the state-backed association and other groups did not provide food supplements for the growing numbers of refugees in the camp.
Questionable makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to people in need.
A court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis preventing people from running the 72 makeshift shops, but said the prefect Calais' objections were "entirely understandable".
Judge Jean-François Molla said grocery stores, cafes and restaurants have a much bigger role than simply serving food to people who "live in extremely desperate conditions."
He said the premises provide quiet places for refugees and volunteers to meet.
One of the sites threatened with demolition was a café in the camp, Jungle Book Kids, run by a non-profit organization, which offers 200 meals a day, English and French lessons, and asylum counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
A petition to protect the "children's" café was signed by more than 170,000 people.
The Guardian received a letter saying closing the café "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are as young as 8 years old."
The charity Help Refugess and L'Auberge des Migrants estimated on Friday that the number of refugees in the camp had risen to more than 9,000 after a steep rise in arrivals over the summer — the highest ever.
