Big Brother is here, the first surveillance SIM is coming.
You won't escape it.
The new rules will apply to all persons without a Thai passport who decide to purchase a SIM card from a local operator while staying in Thailand.
That is, not only for tourists, but also for people with long-term visas who, for example, work in Thailand or have married there.
Takorn Tantasith, secretary general of the Office of National Broadcasting and Telecommunications Commission, has said there will be no exceptions.
The plan to sell SIM cards intended exclusively for foreigners was presented by the national telecommunications regulator at the beginning of August.
The new measure, which will allow them to be tracked, is planned to be implemented within six months.
According to Tantasith, this is a means of preserving national security that will make it possible to deal with crimes committed by foreigners.
In addition, so-called tourist SIM cards are intended to help detect people who exceed the permitted length of stay.
Within six months, special SIM cards for foreigners should appear alongside SIM cards intended exclusively for Thais.
The difference will be the tracking function, which will be permanently turned on for cards intended for people without a Thai passport.
You won't be able to turn it off.
"This is not the case with SIM cards for Thais because we can always easily track them," Tantasith added.
It should be noted that in Thailand prepaid is not anonymous as in the Czech Republic.
The seller requires proof of identity.
On the other hand, for several years, one of the operators gave out free starter SIM cards to tourists at airports.
They were fully anonymous.
Ten telecoms regulators from other Asian countries, including Malaysia and Singapore, are considering introducing the same measure as Thailand.
There is currently a mandatory SIM registration in these countries, but legal use of the tracking system is not possible.
However, the planned measure does not mean an obligation for foreigners to purchase a SIM card from a local operator when entering the country.
Of course, they can use roaming services with their own home SIM, in which case the Thai authorities will be short on them.
The operators of a given country only know the relevant network information when they cross the border, that is to say, when the SIM has logged on to their network.
So they know the phone number, but not the owner's information.
However, the difference in roaming prices compared to local operators is so abysmal that even most tourists start looking for local SIM cards during their stay in Thailand.
The authorities' efforts to supervise the movement of foreigners have been met with immediate criticism by foreigners legally living in Thailand.
Tantasith calms the situation and compares the planned system to the obligation to provide a residential address in immigration documents.
In addition, the police will need a warrant to track a specific person.
Any abuse of the system will be punished by an unspecified penalty.
"If a service provider tracks the location of a SIM without a warrant, it will be charged with a crime," Tantasith added.
In addition, the system should maximise the use of prepaid cards.
While at present, a specific number will be recycled only after a 90-day period after which the SIM has not logged in to the network, the number could be renewed after fifteen days if leaving Thailand.
