I think that our collection of mostly Czech authors, including works by Karel Malich, Karel Vysušil, Václav Špála and Otto Gutfreund, helped the architect to orientate herself in our tastes.
Also, the combination of black, white and walnut wood was the architect's idea as well as individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. We then jointly verified whether everything fits together using visualizations.
Were there any complications during the implementation that forced you to give up the original ideas or, on the contrary, accept new ones?
Perhaps only in the initial phase of the project, when we came to the construction site at the moment when it was first possible to climb to the height of our floor, and found that the views we had planned were actually shading the surrounding buildings.
At that time, we fundamentally changed the layout literally overnight.
Granite was used on the kitchen counter and on the paneling of the fireplace wall.
The interior is dominated by wooden surfaces complemented by leather, for example on the upholstery of Norma dining and bar stools from Arper.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you planning any changes here or is there something you wish you had differently today?
I believe that it is a modern, airy interior that primarily fulfills its purpose.
We are not planning any changes, most of the modifications after moving in took place in the level of shading and occupation of terraces.
Perhaps the only criticism is the floor, when walnut wood turns out to be too delicate in a household with a dog.
A word from the architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerová and MgA. Kamila Hornychová, authors of the realization.
The apartment is on the top floor of a new building, so it was possible to make a completely new layout and several other modifications within the building.
For the interior, an important element is the placement of light guides in the ceiling of the corridor and the main toilet.
This gave us daylight into the darker areas of the apartment.
Also, direct access from the main bathroom to the roof terrace to the USSPA pool is one of the building modifications that was very beneficial for the function of the entire apartment.
It also features a swimming pool and a hot tub.
Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You come from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, not far from the Spanish border.
I moved quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, which led me to work for a magazine.
So why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was beginning to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere among people.
It seemed to me that every Frenchman is terribly negative.
People in France are generally negative, but it's gotten worse lately.
It's interesting that you mention negativism.
Some people evaluate the Czech character in this way.
Believe me, you are not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not think so when they come to France, because they don't perceive it as tourists.
But for me it was too much.
Money, for example, is a big topic.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
Now there is also the problem of people's behavior towards Muslims.
This is completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking down on me just because I was a Muslim.
As if I were some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel comfortable in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I admit that I didn't know Prague at all at first.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I didn't know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here for three years now and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of the completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it's because I don't speak Czech, so I can't catch any negative reactions or swearing, but I feel that people are freer here.
That I can do anything, dress any way, and no one will judge me.
In France, you are always looked at unpleasantly, for example, when you have special clothes and so on.
In Prague I started to feel really free.
I don't think the people of Prague care about such things.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then another friend and I started a website where people offer and search for shared housing.
So far we operate only in Prague, but we would like to extend it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends here, who are half Czech, and two Czech friends.
I have to say that another specificity of Czechs is that they initially keep more distance.
They don't let someone near their body right away.
That's quite different from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses each other on the cheek.
It's different here, but I understand that it's a cultural thing, so I try to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, it is quite easy for me in Prague, because almost everyone here speaks English.
Even in convenience stores or grocery stores.
I would like to learn Czech, but I don't have that much time.
And since everyone can communicate at least a little in English, I don't have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there is someone to help me.
Have you encountered any negative reactions?
Maybe because you're a Muslim?
Not really.
Maybe it's also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, a Czech, once told me about a French football team and said something like this: They are not French, but Africans.
That touched me quite a bit.
But that anyone would have a problem with me being a Muslim, that has not happened to me yet.
This is despite the fact that a colleague once warned me about some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go to the center, that they would scold me there.
The anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels could happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that nowadays anything can happen anywhere.
Until recently, I could not imagine that something like this would happen in France.
And it's not just Muslims.
Moreover, Islam does not recognize violence at all.
To me, people who kill are not Muslims.
The Qur'an says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel about terrorists shielding themselves with your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even though I shouldn't feel that way at all.
I try not to follow the violence reports too much, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that isn't really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for terrorists?
We met on Jiřího z Poděbrad Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians demonstrated against the violence.
Did you notice it?
I didn't know about that.
But my understanding is that these people feel the need to prove that they don't agree with violence.
I don't think they need to do something like that.
Why should they feel guilty about something they didn't cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
For example, my co-workers are from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They are a bit more religious than I am, so we sometimes have quite wild discussions about Islam because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, for example, they learned Islam at school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordination of women.
How do you see it?
I don't feel subordinate in any way.
Quite the opposite.
I am a woman, I have strength.
This is also related to the fact that you do not wear any headgear.
For example, the hijab?
And it's mainly due to the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a really principled Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he just doesn't wear a headscarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It is up to everyone how they interpret it.
When one reads the Qur'an, one should form one's own opinion on these things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur'an that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the wife of the Prophet, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect it, and when I travel to Iran or Saudi Arabia, where headscarves are required, I take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
Nowhere else did I feel so good.
I thought about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
In my opinion, Prague is the ideal city for this.
Czech Muslims together with Christians demonstrated against violence.
