Thirty years ago, when I retired, my wife, after thirty years of marriage, found a man twenty years younger, our neighbor.
I knew it from the beginning - at first she had obviously been trying for a long time, then they got together.
He's such a big guy, probably her type, because she used to date a similar one before me.
She was completely crazy about him.
In those first days, her voice even changed, she had this girlish, amorous voice.
But when I told her I knew what was going on, she denied it.
But I watched the whole thing.
Back then he regularly came home from work at half past four, so she always left at three to go shopping.
Every day she tried to at least see him.
Later I found out that they were meeting in his house, in the laundry.
How many times I knew they were there.
I got my keys, determined to catch them there.
But I don't know why, in the end I always stayed at home.
I was never able to go there, to take that decisive step.
You may laugh at me, but I believe my wife controlled my mind.
I think she soon found out that I was controllable, that I would do what she wanted.
And I did.
Maybe I'm just a slipper.
At the same time, the neighbors indicated to me that she also knew about it.
I was such a fool that I never asked them what to do.
I was afraid that if it all broke, it would be bad.
Only my daughter knew that it would affect everyone in the family.
So I always put it off, on and on.
But one day I went to his apartment and said I needed help with something in the laundry room.
He went there with me and I told him that I had received an anonymous message, that he was meeting my wife and that everything seemed to indicate this.
I asked him what he had to say.
He stood there, shrugging his shoulders, staring at the ground, and not saying a word.
Then, at that time, I met his wife on the way home from the store.
I told her, but she didn't believe it at all.
She didn't react to it and didn't tell me anything.
Nobody told me anything at the time.
I'm the kind of person who has never really gone anywhere, who has trouble getting to know someone, let alone finding a woman.
So I didn't even think about divorce.
I kept counting on it to end one day.
I told myself that I would forgive her all this and life would go on.
But that was not the case.
And I basically never came to terms with it all.
I still have it in me to this day.
I used to let her know it quite often, but in the end I gave it up for peace of mind.
He continues to live in the house next door and I continue to live with her.
Only she is more than my wife my housekeeper.
At home, she always did everything - cooked, washed, cleaned.
She is hardworking.
I think she always tried to make sure I had no other reason to complain.
And you can say that she is also good.
But sometimes I would like to stroke her, hug her, and she will not let go.
We go for walks and shopping together, and everyone thinks what a happy marriage we have.
But she once told me that she never loved me.
That she loved me, but that she didn't love me.
And I see that she loves him to this day, he is her god.
And I don't enjoy such a life.
Even when it started and I took it very badly, I once told her that I didn't want to live and asked her what she would say if I ended it.
I wanted to know if she would agree or not.
And that's what I wanted to hear from her: Yes or no.
But she thought about it and finally said, "But there is plenty of room here."
Prime Minister Manuel Valls wants to establish a new French Islamic Foundation to serve as a bridge between the state and its Muslim inhabitants.
After the terrorist attacks, France is stepping up its fight against radical Islamists, calling on the government and the local Muslim minority to help.
"If Muslims themselves do not help the state against those who violate public freedom, it will be increasingly difficult for France to guarantee their freedom of religion," Prime Minister Manuel Valls said.
He intends to ensure that only the spiritually educated in France preach in the country.
He also wants to stop the financing of mosques from abroad, where preachers indoctrinated with jihad often come with the money.
By October, Prime Minister Valls wants to establish a new French Islamic Foundation to serve as a bridge between the state and its Muslim inhabitants.
The new institution will replace the current French Foundation for Islam, founded in 2005 by then-Prime Minister Dominique de Villepin.
Even then, it was supposed to contribute to making the financial flows between mosques and the countries that finance their construction more transparent.
Soon, however, internal contradictions hit it and it never functioned properly.
"It's a total failure," Valls said.
The new foundation is likely to be headed by former Interior and Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevènement, who is known as a champion of the secular state.
There are about 2500 mosques and places of worship in France, about 120 of which serve radical Islamism.
Since 2012, French authorities have expelled some 80 Islamic clerics from the country and are considering several dozen more.
This week, German police also cracked down on jihadist clerics.
The imams reportedly recruited fighters for the Islamic State.
One of them operated a space where worshippers allegedly became radicalized and later attacked a Sikh temple in Essen.
Immediately after the attacks on Charlie Hebdo in January 2015, a debate erupted in France about a new institution to replace the defunct foundation.
Everything was precipitated by other terrorist attacks carried out by radical Islamists in the name of the Islamic State.
The new foundation will have two main tasks – to ensure domestic funding for mosques and to supervise imams.
However, it is not yet clear where it will get funding, although several proposals are under consideration.
One of them is a special levy on halal foods, i.e. mainly meat derived from slaughter according to Islamic principles.
In practice, this tax would be paid by halal food vendors for granting permits.
Part of the money would then go to the foundation's budget.
A contribution of 10 to 20 euros could also be paid by French pilgrims who go to Mecca.
Every year, about 30,000 of them set out from France on a traditional pilgrimage to Saudi Arabia.
Moreover, only preachers who have undergone educational programs at their universities should work in French mosques.
Because of this, their preaching should be in harmony with democracy.
The government is also closing radical mosques.
"We have closed twenty since December and more will follow," Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve said.
"There is no place in France for those who preach hatred and do not respect the principles of our country, such as equality between women and men," he said.
