Centcom's leadership failure extends to the top of the organization.
The ten-page report details the Central Staff's ongoing problems in describing and analyzing U.S. efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While there is no conclusive evidence that top Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be altered, the report said analysts felt they were pressured by Centcom leaders to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic State, or IS.
"In the first half of 2015, many press releases from the Central Staff, statements and congressional statements were significantly more positive than what events actually were," the report said.
For example, a Centcom official has publicly stated that a major military offensive to take Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
"This is very clear after months of investigation," Rep. Mike Pompeo, a representative of the Republican Party from Kansas, said in a statement.
