"A generation of protesters" in Ethiopia, a longtime ally of the US
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have met with violent resistance from the government.
Witnesses say many protesters were shot dead during clashes with police.
Is war imminent in Ethiopia?
For the past decade, it has been one of the most stable nations in Africa, a solid Western alliance with a rapidly growing economy.
In recent months, however, anti-government unrest has engulfed the country and is spreading to more and more areas.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding fundamental political changes.
According to human rights organizations, the government's response has been merciless.
Witnesses say police shot and killed crowds of unarmed protesters.
Circulating videos of the protests, believed to date back to late last year or early this year, show members of the security forces beating young people with sticks after being forced to stand on their hands against a wall.
The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together and taking a step forward will be even harder," said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project for the International Crisis Group's research group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa after Nigeria and its stability is supported by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence agencies work closely with Ethiopians to counteract the threat of terrorist attack in the region, particularly in Somalia, and few, if any, African countries receive such assistance from the West.
Ethiopia's economy developed at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And the streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - human rights organisations talk incessantly of government repression - opposition in the country has been suppressed, dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were banished, imprisoned, killed or driven far out into the desert.
However, this may change.
"When you choke people and they have no choice but to protest, there is a breakthrough," said Seyoum Teshome, who lectures at a university in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
A whole generation is protesting.
The complaints are many, ranging from land disputes to absolute control of the ruling coalition's power.
After last year's elections, which were widely criticized, the ruling party and its allies won the last opposition-held seat and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, pressure is mounting on the border with Eritrea. The conflict along this inaccurately marked, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less suppressed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to take advantage of the confusion and re-arm themselves.
There are several factors that explain why, after years of smoldering beneath the surface, these bitter feelings have flared up again.
The first is seemingly harmless: smartphones.
Many Ethiopians have only been able to communicate through social networks in the last few years, when cheaper smartphones have become widely available and Internet service delivery has improved.
And even if the government bans access to Facebook or Twitter, as is commonly the case during protests, many people can still communicate through internet proxies that hide the location of these people.
Several young Ethiopians spoke about how they gathered for the protests.
There is also greater solidarity between the Oroma and the Amhara, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromoo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For long ages, the Amhara, mainly from the Christian hills of Ethiopia, excelled in politics and trade, taking advantage of the Oromöms, many of whom are Muslim and live in the lowlands.
But that's also changing.
"We are on the road to unified leadership," said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of the Orom.
The largest protests took place in areas inhabited by Amhara and Orom.
Many Amhara and Oromo believe Ethiopia is unjustly dominated by the Tigrayi ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls the military, intelligence, commerce and politics.
The third reason for the riots is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012 when he succumbed to an unmentioned disease.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at detecting early signs of discontent and using envoys to process opponents and win them over to his side.
"The current regime lacks basic knowledge," said Abdi, an analyst of the conflict.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, has been pulled out of relative obscurity in order to replace Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he has no confidence in Tigrayan-controlled security services.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested what analysts said was an election that the government had cowardly and then stolen.
