NASA Climate Model: Venus Was Once Habitable
According to projections of NASA's new climate model, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for exploring Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether conditions similar to those on Earth could once have existed on Venus, which is hot, waterless and saturated with CO2.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' low rotational speed can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
According to the latest simulations, however, it seems that Venus may once have a thin Earth-like atmosphere while rotating slowly.
The model also dealt with an earlier topography of Venus.
There were probably drier areas on the planet than on Earth, but there was once enough water and geographical diversity to support life and provide protection against rapid evaporation.
Venus previously also used the Sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"In the GISS simulation, Venus exposes its day side to the sun during its slow rotation for almost two moons at once," GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a new report.
This heats up the surface and creates rain, which creates a dense layer of clouds that act like an umbrella and shield the surface from too much solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than currently on Earth.
The model constructed a story of Venus similar to an evolution previously hypothetically constructed by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past — over the course of billions of years — it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light.
Its oceans evaporated and water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen escaped, leaving only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly effect of a greenhouse gas -- this is Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their results from a new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
