Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades
The Kepler Space Telescope's latest mission to help astronomers is to obtain a nearly complete list of stellar rotation speeds from the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data are helping astronomers understand why the cluster's stars spin at different speeds, and how rotation time relates to planet formation.
"By comparing our results with other star clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between stellar matter, its age, and even the history in its solar system," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena.
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the cluster's stars are now reaching maturity and formed over 125 million years ago.
Now it rotates the fastest.
At moments of maximum rotation speeds, these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a retarding effect on them.
As the star ages, so does its rotational speed.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star by measuring the time between the appearance of recognizable points on stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull likens stars to dancers, with larger ones pirouetting more slowly than smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades Ballet, we see that the slower spinning stars are more massive, while the ones that spin the fastest are usually very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing star quality and rotational speeds.
"The Pleiades provide an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, for younger and older stars," Rebull said.
There's still a lot we want to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down their rotation speed and "hang up their dancing shoes," so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the rotational velocities of the Pleiades in three studies that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a qualification agreement necessary?
If I did not apply, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could transfer to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work after graduation without enrolling in specialized education?
My point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a slightly more distant hospital, but in about half a year there could be a vacancy in another where I would then like to work.
So I don't know how to deal with the situation for about six months, the question continues.
Mgr. Lenka Vlková answers.
No legal regulation provides for the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - the hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institute regulated by the Labour Code and may be concluded between an employee and an employer in order to ensure the return of costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee's qualifications.
In the health sector, there is a long-standing pressure not to conclude such agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of healthcare professionals, and not all hospitals currently require such an agreement.
Pursuant to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on conditions for obtaining and recognizing professional qualifications and specialized qualifications for the performance of the medical profession of doctor, dentist and pharmacist, participation in specialized education is considered to be deepening of qualifications (not their increase).
This means that a qualification agreement can only be concluded under the Labour Code if the costs amount to at least CZK 75,000.
No legal regulation stipulates the obligation to enrol in specialized education.
The law only lays down the conditions for an application for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to practice the profession of doctor already thanks to the completion of the necessary university studies, albeit under the conditions laid down by law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The Act foresees a situation in which professional experience completed in another field of specialization may be included in the specialised education of a doctor, provided that its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational programme.
Theoretically, it would be possible to take into account the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the interviewer's situation.
However, with regard to the fact that I do not know the more detailed circumstances of this case, it is advisable to consult the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (Department of Science and Medical Professions), as the Ministry of Health by law provides advisory and consulting services related to inclusion in specialized education and its course.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
