The UN's chief humanitarian operations, Stephen O'Brien, welcomed the move, but stressed the need for at least a two-day ceasefire.
According to AFP, 15 of the 35 doctors who work in the rebel-held eastern part of Aleppo have addressed Obama in a letter.
They write that during the five-year war they witnessed the violent, cruel deaths of countless patients, friends and colleagues.
The world looks on and notes how complex Syria is, but does little to protect us.
Recent offers to evacuate the population from the Syrian regime and Russia sound like thinly veiled threats, pediatricians, surgeons and other doctors have noted.
Doctors said 42 attacks on medical facilities in Syria had been recorded in the past month, including 15 on the hospitals where they work.
What saddens us most is that we have to decide who will live and who will die.
Young children come to the emergency room with such serious injuries that we have to choose among them those who are most likely to survive.
And sometimes we don't even have the necessary material to help them, doctors described.
Two weeks ago, four newborns suffocated when an explosion cut off the supply of oxygen to their incubators.
They gasped for breath and then their lives ended - before it could really begin, they recalled.
The army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, backed by Russian forces, in recent weeks surrounded the rebel-controlled eastern part of Aleppo, inside found themselves without food supplies over 200,000 people.
The rebels, who are under constant strikes from the Russian and Syrian air forces, managed to break the encirclement and launch a counteroffensive on Saturday after three weeks.
Both sides then added reinforcements in the city and its surroundings.
